 {{cite book|title=The Brooke Book |first=Brooke |last=Shields |publisher=Pocket Books |date=1978 |isbn=978-0-671-79018-9 }}\n* {{cite book |title=On Your Own |first=Brooke |last=Shields |date=1985 |publisher=Villard |isbn=978-0-394-54460-1 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/onyourown00shie }}\n* {{cite book|title=Down Came the Rain: My Journey Through Postpartum Depression |first=Brooke |last=Shields |date=2006 |publisher=Hyperion |isbn=978-1-61553-007-6 }}\n* {{cite book|title=It's the Best Day Ever, Dad! |first1=Brooke |last1=Shields |publisher=Middle Grade |date=2009 |isbn= 978-0-06-172445-9 |others=Illustrated by Cori Doerrfeld }}\n* {{cite book|title=There Was a Little Girl: The Real Story of My Mother and Me |first=Brooke |last=Shields |date=2014 |publisher=Dutton Adult |isbn=978-0-525-95484-2}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Brooke Shields}}\n* {{IMDb name|222}}\n* {{tcmdb name|id=176362|name=Brooke Shields}}\n* {{IBDB name}}\n* {{iobdb name|9318}}\n* [http://my.webmd.com/content/Article/104/107292.htm?pagenumber=1 WebMD article on Shields and Postpartum Depression]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090304204142/http://thelonelyisland.com/episodes.html \"Regarding Ardy\": an online short film with Brooke Shields]\n* [http://www.runawaybunnymusic.com/ \"The Runaway Bunny\" violin concerto, by Glen Roven and narrated by Brooke Shields]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20081012034152/http://sidewalkstv.com/webclips/s/brookeshields.html Brooke Shields 2007 Interview] on ''[[Sidewalks Entertainment]]''\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20081016090551/http://www.funnyordie.com/videos/2326 Brooke Shields 2007 short film] on ''[[Funny Or Die]]''\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shields, Brooke}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:20th-century American writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:Actresses from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Actresses from New York City]]\n[[Category:Actresses of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:American child actresses]]\n[[Category:American child models]]\n[[Category:American female models]]\n[[Category:American children's writers]]\n[[Category:Actresses from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Female models from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American memoirists]]\n[[Category:American musical theatre actresses]]\n[[Category:American people of English descent]]\n[[Category:American people of French descent]]\n[[Category:American people of German descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Scotch-Irish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Welsh descent]]\n[[Category:Actresses of German descent]]\n[[Category:American Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:American soap opera actresses]]\n[[Category:American socialites]]\n[[Category:American stage actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:American writers of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:Dwight-Englewood School alumni]]\n[[Category:House of Torlonia]]\n[[Category:People from Haworth, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:People from Greenwich Village]]\n[[Category:Princeton University alumni]]\n[[Category:Women memoirists]]\n[[Category:Women children's writers]]\n[[Category:Writers from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Writers from New York City]]\n[[Category:American women non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Catholics from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Catholics from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:American women activists]]\n[[Category:People from the Upper East Side]]\n[[Category:People from Manhattan]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2018}}\n{{short description|American actress and model}}\n{{pp-semi-blp|small=yes}}{{Infobox person\n| name        = Brooke Shields\n| image       = Brooke Shields 2011 (Cropped).jpg\n| caption     = Shields in November 2011\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1965|05|31}}\n| birth_place = [[Manhattan|Manhattan, New York]], U.S.\n| residence   = Manhattan, New York, U.S.\n| alma mater  = [[Princeton University]]\n| yearsactive = 1966\u2013present\n| occupation  = Actress, model\n| spouse      = {{marriage|[[Andre Agassi]]|1997|1999|reason=divorced}}<br />{{marriage|[[Chris Henchy]]|2001}}\n| children    = 2\n| parents     = [[Francis Alexander Shields|Frank Shields]]<br />[[Teri Shields]]\n| relatives   = [[Francis Xavier Shields]] (grandfather)<br />[[Marina Torlonia di Civitella-Cesi|Donna Marina Torlonia]] (grandmother)\n}}\n\n'''Brooke Christa Shields''' (born May 31, 1965) is an American actress and model. She was initially a [[child model]] and gained critical acclaim at age 12 for her leading role in [[Louis Malle]]'s film ''[[Pretty Baby (1978 film)|Pretty Baby]]'' (1978), in which she played a [[child prostitute]] in [[New Orleans]] at the beginning of the 20th century. Shields garnered widespread notoriety in the role, and she continued to model into her late teenage years and starred in several dramas in the 1980s, including ''[[The Blue Lagoon (1980 film)|The Blue Lagoon]]'' (1980), and [[Franco Zeffirelli]]'s ''[[Endless Love (1981 film)|Endless Love]]'' (1981).\n\nIn 1983, Shields suspended her career as a model to attend [[Princeton University]], where she graduated with a [[bachelor's degree]] in Romance Languages.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Initiation: From Innocence to Experience: The Pre-Adolescent/Adolescent Journey in the Films of Louis Malle, \"Pretty Baby\" and \"Lacombe Lucien\" |url=http://arks.princeton.edu/ark:/88435/dsp01qr46r1433|website=Princeton University Undergraduate Senior Theses, 1924\u20132016|accessdate=September 23, 2016}}</ref> In the 1990s, Shields returned to acting and appeared in minor roles in films. She also starred in the [[NBC]] [[sitcoms]] ''[[Suddenly Susan]]'' (1996\u20132000), for which she received two [[Golden Globe]] nominations, and ''[[Lipstick Jungle (TV series)|Lipstick Jungle]]'' (2008\u20132009).<ref name=actors>Stated on ''[[Inside the Actors Studio]]'', 2008</ref> In 2017, Shields returned to NBC with a major recurring role in ''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit]]'' in the show's 19th season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cinemablend.com/television/1691229/law--order-svu-season-19-is-adding-brooke-shields-for-a-big-role|title=Law & Order: SVU Season 19 Is Adding Brooke Shields For A Big Role|author=Laura Hurley|publisher=CinemaBlend|date=August 11, 2017|accessdate=August 11, 2017}}</ref> Since 2014, Shields has voiced Beverly Goodman in the [[Adult Swim]] animated series ''[[Mr. Pickles]]'' and its  spinoff ''[[Momma Named Me Sheriff]]''.\n\n== Early life ==\nBrooke Christa Shields<ref name=actors /> was born in [[Manhattan|Manhattan, New York]]<ref name=BIO /> on May 31, 1965,<ref name=BIO>{{cite web | url = http://www.biography.com/people/brooke-shields-9542246 | title =Brooke Shields Biography | publisher = Biography.com / [[Fyi (TV network)|Fyi]] ([[A&E Networks]])| accessdate= November 12, 2014}}</ref> the daughter of actress and model [[Teri Shields]] (''n\u00e9e'' Schmon; 1933\u20132012) and businessman [[Francis Alexander Shields|Frank Shields]] (1941\u20132003). Her mother was of [[English people|English]], [[Germans|German]], [[Ulster Scots people|Scotch-Irish]], and [[Welsh people|Welsh]] descent,<ref>{{cite news |title=Meeting the ancestors |url=http://www.rte.ie/ten/2010/0705/blog_tv_tvwatch.html | archive-url=https://archive.today/20130217201624/http://www.rte.ie/ten/2010/0705/blog_tv_tvwatch.html | url-status=dead | archive-date=February 17, 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maryellenmark.com/text/magazines/life/905W-000-017.html|title=LIFE MAGAZINE \u2013 AMERICA FALLS FOR A MILLION DOLLAR BABY \u2013 905W-000-017|publisher=}}</ref> while her father had English, [[French people|French]], [[Irish people|Irish]], and [[Italians|Italian]] ancestry.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bostonherald.com/entertainment/television/general/view.bg?articleid=1237292|title=Television \u2013 Boston Herald|publisher=|access-date=March 9, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100307025455/http://www.bostonherald.com/entertainment/television/general/view.bg?articleid=1237292|archive-date=March 7, 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref> According to research by [[William Addams Reitwiesner]], Shields has ancestral links with a number of noble families from Italy, in particular from [[Genoa]] and [[Rome]].<ref name=Reitwiesner>{{cite web|url=http://www.wargs.com/essays/lesbian.html|title=Lesbian Genealogy|publisher=}}</ref> These are namely (in chronological order of descent from 1355 to 1965) the [[Francesco I Gattilusio|Gattilusi]]-[[Andronikos III Palaiologos#Family|Palaiologos]]-[[Anna of Savoy|Savoy]], [[House of Grimaldi|Grimaldi]], [[Imperiali family|Imperiali]], [[House of Carafa|Carafa]], [[Doria (family)|Doria]], [[Doria-Pamphili-Landi]], [[Chigi-Albani]], and [[House of Torlonia|Torlonia]] dynasties.<ref name=Reitwiesner /> Her paternal grandmother was Italian noblewoman [[Marina Torlonia di Civitella-Cesi]], who was the daughter of an [[Marino Torlonia, 4th Prince of Civitella-Cesi|Italian prince]] and an [[Mary Elsie Moore|American socialite]].<ref name=Reitwiesner />\n\nWhen Teri announced that she was pregnant, Frank's family paid her a sum to terminate the pregnancy. Teri took the money, but violated the agreement and gave birth to Shields.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2012/12/30/magazine/the-lives-they-lived-2012.html |title=The Lives They Lived |work=The New York Times|accessdate=December 30, 2012 |date=December 28, 2012}}</ref> Frank married Teri, but they were divorced when Shields was five months old.<ref>[http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20645378,00.html#disqus_thread \"Brooke Shields's Mother, Teri Shields, Dies at 79\"]. ''People''. November 6, 2012.</ref> She has two stepbrothers and three half-sisters.<ref>{{cite book|last=Shields|first=B|title=Welcome to Your World, Baby|url=https://archive.org/details/welcometoyourwor0000shie|url-access=registration|publisher= HarperCollins|year=2008|page=6}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.seeing-stars.com/Churches/StMonicas.shtml |title=St. Monica Church |first=Gary |last=Wayne |publisher= |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100817145240/http://www.seeing-stars.com/Churches/StMonicas.shtml |archivedate=August 17, 2010 |df= }}</ref> When Shields was only five days old, her mother openly stated she wanted her to be active in show business, saying, \"She's the most beautiful child and I'm going to help her with her career.\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Conner|first=Floyd|title=Hollywood's Most Wanted|page=[https://archive.org/details/hollywoodsmostwa0000conn/page/107 107]|url=https://archive.org/details/hollywoodsmostwa0000conn|url-access=registration|quote=...Her beauty was going to contribute to mankind.|year=2002|publisher=Brassey's|isbn=1-57488-480-8}}</ref> Growing up, Shields took piano, ballet, and [[Equestrianism|horse riding]] lessons.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.goodhousekeeping.com/family/celebrity-interviews/brooke-shields-interview-2 |title=Being Brooke |magazine=Good Housekeeping |date= |first=Jenny |last=Allen |accessdate=November 13, 2014 |page=2 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141128015257/http://www.goodhousekeeping.com/family/celebrity-interviews/brooke-shields-interview-2 |archive-date=November 28, 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nShields was raised in the [[Catholic Church|Roman Catholic]] faith.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://movies.yahoo.com/movie/contributor/1800014914/bio |title=Brooke Shields |publisher=[[Yahoo! Movies]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110628225921/http://movies.yahoo.com/movie/contributor/1800014914/bio |archivedate=June 28, 2011 }}</ref> For her [[Confirmation (Catholic Church)|confirmation]] at age 10, she took the name \"[[Camillus de Lellis|Camille]].\" While attending high school, she resided in [[Haworth, New Jersey]], across the [[George Washington Bridge]] from Manhattan.<ref>Rondinaro, Gene. [https://www.nytimes.com/1986/01/26/realestate/if-you-re-thinking-of-living-in-haworth.html \"If You Think Of Living In; Haworth\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', January 26, 1986. Accessed February 19, 2007.</ref> Shields has stated that her very first encounter with the paparazzi was in the Grand Ballroom of the [[Waldorf Astoria New York]] at the age of 12, stating that she \"stood like a statue wondering why they were all hired to photograph [her]\" and that she \"[[debutante|debuted]] at the Waldorf.\"<ref>{{cite book |last=Morehouse |first=Ward, III |title=The Waldorf Astoria: America's Gilded Dream |year=1991 |publisher=[[M. Evans]] |isbn=978-1-4134-6504-4 |pages=254\u2013255}}</ref>\n\nShields attended the [[New Lincoln School]] until eighth grade.<ref>[http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20072596,00.html ''People.com: Brooke Shields] Retrieved June 28, 2011</ref><ref name=\"Celebrity Prep School\">{{cite web|url=http://www.celebrityprepschools.com/part5.htm|title=celebrityprepschools.com|publisher=}}</ref> She graduated from the [[Dwight-Englewood School]] in [[Englewood, New Jersey]], in 1983.<ref name=actors /> She moved to a dorm at [[Princeton University]] to pursue her [[bachelor's degree]] in [[French literature]], where she graduated in 1987.<ref name=nymag /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/people/brooke_shields|title=Brooke Shields \u2013 PEOPLE.com|publisher=}}</ref> At Princeton, Shields spoke openly about her sexuality and virginity. She was a member of the [[Princeton Triangle Club]] and the [[Cap and Gown Club]]. Her autobiography, ''On Your Own'', was published in 1985.<ref>Shields, Brooke (1985) ''On Your Own'' New York: [[Villard Books]] pp. 220 {{ISBN|0-394-54460-9}} [[Online Computer Library Center|OCLC]] [http://worldcat.org/oclc/11915327 11915327]</ref> Her 1987 senior thesis was titled \"The Initiation: From Innocence to Experience: The Pre-Adolescent/Adolescent Journey in the Films of [[Louis Malle]], ''[[Pretty Baby (1978 film)|Pretty Baby]]'' and ''[[Lacombe Lucien]]''.\"<ref name=actors />\n\nShortly after Shields graduated from college, her four-year transcript was published in the July 1987 edition of ''[[Life Magazine]]''. Based on that transcript, ''[[The New York Times]]'' published a light-hearted [[op-ed page|op-ed piece]] intended to tweak the claim that Princeton produced superior, well-rounded graduates. Noting that Shields \"got all As and Bs, and obviously paid attention to her school work\", it claimed she \"got cheated\" because Princeton did not require her to take any classical studies, medieval, modern or American history, nor any course in mathematics, philosophy, economics, political science, world literature, or science with laboratory experience. \"[I]f that adds up to a liberal arts education from a place like Princeton, there is no longer any danger that our society will ever suffer from elitism in any form.\"<ref>{{cite book |last=Koppett |first=Leonard |title=At Princeton, They Call it an Education |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/08/15/opinion/at-princeton-they-call-it-an-education.html |date=August 15, 1987 |work=The New York Times}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n=== Early work ===\n[[File:Feb1991 Brooke Shields on Sally Jesse Raphael.jpg|thumb|Shields with the [[Princeton University Band]] for a taping of [[Sally Jessy Raphael]]'s show in Feb 1991]]\nShields began her career as a model when she was 11 months old in 1966. Her first job was for [[Ivory Soap]], when she was shot by [[Francesco Scavullo]].<ref name=actors /> She continued as a successful child model with model agent [[Eileen Ford]], who, in her Lifetime Network biography, stated that she started her children's division just for Shields. Shields worked with director [[Woody Allen]] in his 1977 film [[Annie Hall]], but her role was cut out of the final edit of the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/celebritynews/11279436/Brooke-Shields-I-stuck-up-for-mum-but-now-I-want-a-say.html|title=Brooke Shields: 'I stuck up for mum, but now I want a say'|last1=Walden|first1=Celia|publisher=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|date=December 8, 2014|accessdate=June 10, 2019}}</ref> In 1978, when she was 12 years old, Shields played a child [[prostitute]] in the controversial film ''[[Pretty Baby (1978 film)|Pretty Baby]]''. [[Eileen Ford]], founder of the [[Ford Modeling Agency]], said of Brooke Shields: \"She is a professional child and unique. She looks like an adult and thinks like one.\"<ref>{{cite book |last=Handel |first=Gerald |title=Childhood socialization|page=37|year=2006|publisher=Aldine Transaction |isbn=0-202-30641-0}}</ref>\n\nIn 1980, 14-year-old Shields was the youngest fashion model ever to appear on the cover of [[Vogue (magazine)|''Vogue'']]. Later that same year, Shields appeared in controversial print and TV ads for [[Calvin Klein]] jeans. The TV ad included her saying the famous tagline, \"You want to know what comes between me and my Calvins? Nothing.\"<ref name=actors /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/culture/features/2008/04/calvin200804?currentPage=7|title=Calvin to the Core|first=Ingrid|last=Sischy|publisher=}}</ref><ref>[http://www.style.com/beauty/icon/121407 Style.com ''Brooke Shields'']</ref> Brooke Shields ads would help catapult Klein's career to super-designer status.<ref>{{cite book|last=Hall|first=Ann C.|title=Delights, desires and dilemmas: essays on women and the media|page=xii|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MD2mUa5dxYsC&pg=PR12&cd=58#v=onepage|year=1998|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=0-275-96156-7}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1981 to 1983, Shields, her mother, photographer [[Garry Gross]], and [[Playboy Press]] were involved in litigation in the [[New York City Courts]] over the rights to photographs her mother had signed away to Gross (when dealing with models who are minors, a parent or legal guardian must sign such a release form while other agreements are subject to negotiation). Gross was the photographer of a controversial set of nude images taken in 1975 of a then ten-year-old Brooke Shields with the consent of her mother, Teri Shields, for the Playboy Press publication Sugar 'n' Spice. The images portray Shields nude, standing and sitting in a bathtub, wearing makeup and covered in oil.  The courts ruled in favor of the photographer due to a strange twist in New York law. It would have been otherwise had Brooke Shields been considered a child \"performer\" rather than a model.<ref>{{cite book|last=Siegel|first=Paul|title=Communication Law in America|pages=193\u2013194|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_hhqXPqqjOsC&pg=PA193&cd=59#v=onepage|year=2007|isbn=978-0-7425-5387-3}}</ref>\n\nBy the age of 16, Shields had become one of the most recognizable faces in the United States, because of her dual career as a provocative [[Model (person)|fashion model]] and child actress.<ref name=actors /> ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine reported in its February 9, 1981 cover story that her day rate as a model was $10,000. In 1983, Shields appeared on the cover of the September issue of Paris ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]'', the October and November issues of American ''Vogue'' and the December edition of Italian ''Vogue''.<ref name=nymag>{{cite web|url=https://nymag.com/fashion/models/bshields/brookeshields/|title=Brooke Shields \u2013 Fashion Model \u2013 Profile on New York Magazine|work=New York Magazine}}</ref> During that period Shields became a regular at New York City's nightclub [[Studio 54]].<ref>{{cite interview|last=Shields|first= Brooke|subjectlink= Brooke Shields |interviewer=Jimmy Fallon|work=Late Night with Jimmy Fallon|publisher=[[NBC]]|location=[[New York City]]|date=February 7, 2011|accessdate= July 21, 2011|url=http://www.latenightwithjimmyfallon.com/video/brooke-shields-part-1-2711/1287260/|title=Brooke Shields \u2013 Part 1}}</ref> In 2009, a picture of a naked Brooke Shields taken when she was 10 and included in a work by [[Richard Prince]], ''Spiritual America'', created a row. It was removed from an exhibition at the [[Tate Modern]] after a warning from the police.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2009/sep/30/brooke-shields-naked-tate-modern Tate Modern removes naked Brooke Shields picture after police visit] \u2013 [[Charlotte Higgins]] and Vikram Dodd \u2013 ''[[The Guardian]]'' \u2013 September 30, 2009</ref>\n\n=== Film ===\n[[File:Brooke Shields Cannes.jpg|thumb|left|Shields at the [[1998 Cannes Film Festival]]]]\nShields' first major film role was as a lead actress in [[Louis Malle]]'s ''[[Pretty Baby (1978 film)|Pretty Baby]]'' (1978), a movie in which she played a child named Violet who lived in a brothel (in which there were numerous nude scenes).<ref name=actors /> She was only 12 years old when the film was released, and controversy regarding [[child pornography]] arose.<ref>McMurran, Kristen. [http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20070948,00.html \"Pretty Brooke\"], ''People'' (May 29, 1978).</ref><ref>Canby, Vincent. [https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/review?&res=EE05E7DF173EE573BC4D53DFB2668383669EDE&partner=Rotten%20Tomatoes \"Critic's Pick: Pretty Baby,\"] ''The New York Times'' (April 5, 1978).</ref><ref name=\"Ebert\">Ebert, Roger.[http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/19780601/REVIEWS/51012001/1023 \"''Pretty Baby'',\"] ''Chicago Sun-Times'' (June 1, 1978).</ref> This was followed by a slightly less controversial and less notable film, ''[[Wanda Nevada]]'' (1979).\n\nAfter two decades of movies, her best known films are still arguably ''[[The Blue Lagoon (1980 film)|The Blue Lagoon]]'' (1980), which included nude scenes between teenage lovers on a tropical island (Shields later testified before a U.S. Congressional inquiry that older [[body double]]s were used in some of them), and ''[[Endless Love (1981 film)|Endless Love]]'' (1981). The [[Motion Picture Association of America|MPAA]] initially rated ''Endless Love'' with an [[Motion Picture Association of America film rating system|X rating]]. The film was re-edited to earn an [[Motion Picture Association of America film rating system|R rating]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Weekly World News|page=46|date=July 14, 1981 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=r-8DAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA46&cd=19#v=onepage|quote=... She's never been turned on by a kiss...|last1=News|first1=Weekly World}}</ref> She won the [[People's Choice Award]] in the category of Favorite Young Performer in four consecutive years from 1981 to 1984. In 1998, she played a lesbian, Lily, in ''[[The Misadventures of Margaret]]''.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Advocate|date=December 23, 1997|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lWMEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PT11&cd=38#v=onepage|publisher=Here}}</ref>\n\nIn 2001, [[Lifetime (TV network)|Lifetime]] aired the film ''[[What Makes a Family]]'', starring Shields and [[Cherry Jones]] in a true story of a [[lesbian]] couple who fought the adoption laws of [[Florida]].<ref>{{cite book|title=The Advocate|pages=28\u201330|date=January 31, 2001|quote='I really believe that if you are against gays and lesbians adopting and you watch this movie,' you will never feel that way again, promises executive producer [[Craig Zadan]].|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sWMEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA28&cd=17#v=onepage |publisher=Here}}</ref>\n\n=== Television appearances ===\nShields began her television career at an early age. In 1980, she was the youngest guest star to ever appear on ''[[The Muppet Show]]'', in which she and the Muppets put on their own version of ''[[Alice's Adventures in Wonderland]]''. She was also the youngest person to host [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]'s ''[[Fridays (TV series)|Fridays]]'', a ''[[Saturday Night Live]]''-like sketch comedy show, in 1981. In one episode of the popular comedy sitcom ''[[Friends]]'', Shields played [[Joey Tribbiani|Joey]]'s stalker. This role led directly to her being cast in the [[NBC]] sitcom ''[[Suddenly Susan]]'', in which she starred from 1996 until 2000, and which earned a [[People's Choice Award]] in the category of Favorite Female Performer in a New Television Series for her, in 1997, and two [[Golden Globe]] nominations.<ref name=actors />\n\nIn the early 1980s, she starred in the [[USPHS]] [[Public service announcement|PSA]] sponsored by the [[American Lung Association]] as an initiative that [[VIP]]s should become examples and advocates of non-smoking.<ref>{{cite book |last=Campbell |first=George |title=Health, Education and Youth: A Review of Research and Development |page=189 |year=1984 |publisher=Taylor & Francis |isbn=0-905273-54-0}}</ref> In the mid-1980s, Brooke began her support of the [[United Service Organizations|USO]] by touring with [[Bob Hope]].<ref>[http://www.uso.org/uso-entertainment-history.aspx USO History] Retrieved February 11, 2011</ref>\n\n[[File:Brooke Shields 1991Jan.jpg|thumb|Shields aboard the {{USS|Midway|CV-41}} during a [[United Service Organizations|USO]] tour on January 1, 1991]]\nShields made a couple of guest appearances on ''[[That '70s Show]]''. She played Pam Burkhart, [[Jackie Burkhart|Jackie's]] ([[Mila Kunis]]) mother, who later was briefly involved with [[Donna Pinciotti|Donna's]] ([[Laura Prepon]]) father (played by [[Don Stark]]). Shields left ''That '70s Show'' when her character was written out. Shields recorded the narration for the Sony/BMG recording of ''[[The Runaway Bunny (musical composition)|The Runaway Bunny]]'', a concerto for violin, orchestra, and reader, by [[Glen Roven]]. It was performed by the [[Royal Philharmonic]] and [[Ittai Shapira]].\n\nIn 1993, she made a guest appearance in a Season 4 episode, called \"The Front.\" <ref>=[[The Front (The Simpsons)]]</ref>\n\nIn the late 2000s, Shields guest-starred on shows like [[FX (TV channel)|FX]]'s ''[[Nip/Tuck]]'' and [[CBS]]' ''[[Two and a Half Men]]''. In 2005, Shields appeared in a season-two episode of HBO's ''Entourage'', entitled \"Blue Balls Lagoon.\" In 2007, she made a guest appearance on Disney's ''[[Hannah Montana]]'', playing Susan Stewart, Miley and Jackson's mother, who died in 2004. In 2008, she returned in the primetime drama ''[[Lipstick Jungle (TV series)|Lipstick Jungle]]''. The series ended a year later.<ref name=actors />\n\nStarting in 2010, she made guest appearances on ''[[The Middle (TV series)|The Middle]]'' as the mother of a brood of terror-inducing children and the nemesis of Frankie Heck (played by [[Patricia Heaton]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.upi.com/Entertainment_News/TV/2009/12/22/Brooke-Shields-to-appear-on-The-Middle/UPI-97821261498808|title=Brooke Shields to appear on 'The Middle'|publisher=}}</ref><ref>[http://www.tvgrapevine.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=5968:the-middle-a-double-whammie&catid=129:the-middle \"The Middle: A Double Whammie\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100102015443/http://tvgrapevine.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=5968%3Athe-middle-a-double-whammie&catid=129%3Athe-middle |date=January 2, 2010 }} December 30, 2009, TV Grapevine</ref> She also appeared as a featured celebrity in [[NBC]]'s genealogy documentary reality series, [[Who Do You Think You Are? (U.S. TV series)|''Who Do You Think You Are?'']], where it was revealed that, through her father's ancestry, she is the distant cousin (many generations removed) of [[King Louis XIV]] of France, and thus a descendant of both [[Louis IX of France|Saint Louis]] and [[Henry IV of France]].<ref>[http://www.nbc.com/who-do-you-think-you-are/bios/brookeS.shtml Bio] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100406025900/http://www.nbc.com/who-do-you-think-you-are/bios/brookeS.shtml |date=April 6, 2010 }} ''Who Do You Think You Are'', NBC web site</ref>\n\nStarting in 2013, Shields has been an occasional guest co-host in the 9:00 hour of ''[[Today (U.S. TV program)|Today]]'' on NBC.\n\n=== Theater ===\nShields has appeared in several [[Broadway theater|Broadway]] musical theater productions. She played Rizzo in the 1994 revival of ''[[Grease (musical)|Grease]]''. For four months, beginning July 2001, she played Sally Bowles in the long-running 1998 revival of ''[[Cabaret (musical)|Cabaret]]''.<ref name=\"Person List\">{{cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/personlistpage/person-list|title=Person List|website=Playbill}}</ref> In September 2004, Shields replaced [[Donna Murphy]] in the role of Ruth Sherwood in the 2003 revival of ''[[Wonderful Town]]'' until the show closed four months later.<ref name=\"Person List\"/> Her performance was widely praised.<ref name=\"chicago-playbil-announcement\">{{cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/brooke-shields-is-foxy-roxie-hart-in-broadways-chicago-sept-9-com-127909|title=Brooke Shields Is Foxy Roxie Hart in Broadway's Chicago Sept. 9|first=Andrew|last=Gans|date=September 9, 2005|website=Playbill}}</ref> [[Ben Brantley]] of the [[New York Times]] praised the \"goofy sweetness\" she brought to her interpretation of the role, but wrote that she fell short of Donna Murphy's \"perfection.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/10/18/theater/reviews/brooke-shields-as-a-naif-who-cant-get-a-date.html|title=Brooke Shields as a Naif Who Can't Get a Date|first=Ben|last=Brantley|date=October 18, 2004|publisher=|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> In April 2005, Shields played Roxie Hart in a long-running production of ''[[Chicago (musical)|Chicago]]'' at the [[Adelphi Theatre]] in London's West End.<ref name=\"chicago-playbil-announcement\" /> Later the same year, she reprised the role in the Broadway revival, from September 9 to October 30.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibdb.com/broadway-production/chicago-4804|title=Chicago \u2013 Broadway Musical \u2013 1996 Revival - IBDB|website=www.ibdb.com}}</ref> This made her the first performer to have starred in ''Chicago'', ''Cabaret'', and ''Grease'' on Broadway, three long-running revivals noted for \"[[stunt casting]]\" of celebrities not known for musical theatre.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/08/14/theater/newsandfeatures/a-triple-crown.html|title=A Triple Crown|first=Eric|last=Grode|date=August 14, 2005|publisher=|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> She took over the role of [[Morticia Addams]] in the Broadway musical ''[[The Addams Family]]'' on June 28, 2011.<ref>Allen, Olivia.[http://www.ontheredcarpet.com/Brooke-Shields-plays-Morticia-in-Broadways-musical-comedy-The-Addams-Family---Photo/8222341 Brooke Shields plays Morticia in Broadway's musical comedy ''The Addams Family''\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120723000321/http://www.ontheredcarpet.com/Brooke-Shields-plays-Morticia-in-Broadways-musical-comedy-The-Addams-Family---Photo/8222341 |date=July 23, 2012 }} ontheredcarpet.com, June 29, 2011</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nAs a child, she lived with her mother on the [[Upper East Side]].<ref name=\"Thurman\">{{cite news |last1=Thurman |first1=Judith |title=Brooke Shields's House in New York City |url=https://www.architecturaldigest.com/story/brooke-shields-new-york-city-townhouse-article |accessdate=23 March 2019 |publisher=Architectural Digest |date=July 29, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn the June 2009 issue of ''[[Health (magazine)|Health]]'' magazine, Shields related that she lost her virginity at age 22 to actor [[Dean Cain]] while they were dating at Princeton.<ref>{{cite web|work=[[Us Weekly]]|date=December 4, 2014 |url=http://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-news/news/dean-cain-on-brooke-shields-losing-her-virginity-we-were-in-love-2014412 |last=Lee|first=Esther|title=Dean Cain on Brooke Shields Losing Her Virginity}}</ref> She said it would have occurred earlier had she had a better self-image.<ref>{{cite web|work=Health|date= November 6, 2012 |title=Brooke Shields Gives Back: Her Mission to Empower Girls And More|url=https://www.health.com/health/article/0,,20411695,00.html|first=Amy |last=Spencer}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1990s, Shields promoted physical fitness as an extension of femininity, maintaining that femininity and athletics are compatible.<ref>{{cite book|last=Jeynes|first=William|title=American educational history: school, society and the common good |page=270|year=2007|publisher=SAGE|isbn=978-1-4129-1421-5|quote=Several female athletes demonstrated that femininity and athleticism were consistent.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=American Educational History: School, Society, and the Common Good|year=2007|page=270|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FL2WYw0ve-0C&pg=PA270&lpg=PA270#v=onepage|isbn=9781412914215|last1=Jeynes|first1=William}}</ref>\n\nShields is a [[vegan]]<ref>{{cite news|title=A Vegan Meat Locker with a Heartbeat|url=https://tmagazine.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/05/13/artifacts-a-vegan-meat-locker-with-a-heartbeat/? | work=The New York Times | first=Linda|last=Yablonsky|date=May 13, 2010}}</ref> and an [[animal rights]] activist. However, despite coming out against the [[fur industry]] in 1989,<ref>{{cite news|title=Activists Aim to Skin the Fur Industry|url=https://articles.latimes.com/1989-04-30/news/mn-3137_1_anti-fur-fur-free-furriers/2 | work=Los Angeles Times | first=Robert W.|last=Gibson|date=April 30, 1989}}</ref> Shields later went on to create her own mink fur coat at Kopenhagen Fur.<ref>{{cite web|title=Brooke Shields' Inner Child Dreams Of Fur|url=http://www.styleite.com/media/brooke-shields-fur/}}</ref> She came under the scrutiny of [[animal rights]] organizations such as [[PETA]] for this visit, which prompted media attention.<ref>{{cite web|title=Brooke Shields: Fur Nightmare|url=http://www.peta.org/b/thepetafiles/archive/2010/06/01/brooke-shields-fur-nightmare.aspx}}</ref>\n\nShields has been married twice. From 1997 to 1999, she was married to tennis player [[Andre Agassi]]; the couple had been together since 1993.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20128036,00.html|title=Cover Story: Double Fault \u2013 Vol. 51 No. 15|date=April 26, 1999|publisher=}}</ref> Following her divorce from Agassi, she married television writer [[Chris Henchy]] in 2001, after they had met through mutual friends in 1999.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20110122010653/http://today.msnbc.msn.com/id/7748616/page/2/ \"Brooke Shields battles postpartum depression\"]. ''MSNBC''. May 7, 2009. Retrieved June 20, 2010.</ref> They have two daughters<ref>{{cite book|last=Shields|first=Brooke|title=Down Came the Rain: My Journey Through Postpartum Depression|page=63|year=2005|publisher=Hyperion|isbn=1-4013-0189-4 |quote=Rowan Francis}}</ref> and live in [[Greenwich Village]], [[Manhattan]], [[New York City]].<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.architecturaldigest.com/celebrity-homes/2012/brooke-shields-new-york-city-townhouse-article |title=An Exclusive Look at Brooke Shields's Manhattan Home |magazine=Architectural Digest |date=2012 |first=Judith |last=Thurman |accessdate=November 13, 2014 }}</ref> She is a spokeswoman for [[Tupperware]]'s Chain of Confidence SMART Girls campaign, a program that teaches girls to nurture their mental and physical well-being.\n\n=== Postpartum depression ===\nBetween April and May 2005, Shields spoke to magazines (such as ''[[Guideposts (magazine)|Guideposts]]'') and appeared on ''[[The Oprah Winfrey Show]]'' to publicize her battle with [[postpartum depression]], an experience that included depression, thoughts of suicide, an inability to respond to her baby's needs and delayed maternal bonding.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.oprah.com/oprahshow/Postpartum-Depression |title=Postpartum Depression |date=May 4, 2005 |publisher=The Oprah Winfrey Show |accessdate=December 30, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Mann|first=Denise|title=Out of the Blue: Brooke Shields discusses her painful struggle with postpartum depression|url=http://www.webmd.com/depression/postpartum-depression/features/brooke-shields-depression-struggle|work=WebMD|accessdate=July 27, 2013}}</ref> The illness may have been triggered by a traumatic childbirth, the death of her father three weeks earlier, stress from [[in vitro fertilization]], a miscarriage and a family history of depression, as well as the [[hormones]] and life changes which were brought on by childbirth. Her book, ''Down Came the Rain'', discusses her experience,<ref>Shields, Brooke (2005). Down Came the Rain: My Journey Through Postpartum Depression. Hyperion. {{ISBN|1-4013-0189-4}}</ref> contributing to a greater public awareness of postpartum depression.<ref>{{cite book|last=Rosenfield |first= Adrian I.|title=New Research on Postpartum Depression|page=64|year=2006 |publisher=Nova Publishers|isbn=1-60021-284-0|quote=Several popular books have been published in recent years... These include personal accounts... by... Brooke Shields.}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2005, [[Tom Cruise]], an actor and [[Scientology|scientologist]] whose beliefs frown upon [[psychiatry]], condemned Brooke, both personally and professionally, for both using and speaking in favor of the [[antidepressant]] drug [[Paroxetine|Paxil]]. As Cruise said, \"Here is a woman and I care about Brooke Shields, because I think she is an incredibly talented woman, you look at [and think], where has her career gone?\" Shields responded that Cruise's statements about anti-depressants were \"irresponsible\" and \"dangerous.\" She said that he should \"stick to fighting aliens\" (a reference to Cruise's starring role in ''[[War of the Worlds (2005 film)|War of the Worlds]]'' as well as some of the more esoteric aspects of [[Xenu|Scientology doctrine and teachings]]), \"and let mothers decide the best way to treat postpartum depression.\" The actress responded to a further attack by Cruise in an essay \"War of Words\" published in ''[[The New York Times]]'' on July 1, 2005, in which she made an individual case for the medication and said, \"In a strange way, it was comforting to me when my obstetrician told me that my feelings of extreme despair and my suicidal thoughts were directly tied to a biochemical shift in my body. Once we admit that postpartum is a serious medical condition, then the treatment becomes more available and socially acceptable. With a doctor's care, I have since tapered off the medication but, without it, I wouldn't have become the loving parent I am today.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/07/01/opinion/01shields.html|work=The New York Times|title=War of Words|first=Brooke|last=Shields|date=July 1, 2005|accessdate=April 27, 2010}}</ref> On August 31, 2006, according to USAToday.com,<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/people/2006-09-02-shields-cruise_x.htm|work=USA Today|title=Shields: Cruise apology was 'heartfelt'|date=September 2, 2006|accessdate=April 27, 2010}}</ref> Cruise privately apologized to Shields for the incident. Shields accepted Cruise's apology, which she said was \"heartfelt.\" Three months later in November 2006, she and her husband attended the wedding of Cruise and [[Katie Holmes]].\n\n=== Relationship with Michael Jackson ===\nOn July 7, 2009, Shields spoke at the memorial service for [[Michael Jackson]].<ref>[http://www.thefirstpost.co.uk/50269,news,billion-global-viewers-watch-michael-jackson-memorial-service-on-tv Billion watch Jackson send-off on TV] Jack Bremer, ''The First Post'', July 8, 2009</ref> She stated in that speech that she first met Jackson, who was 21 at the time, when she was 13 years old, and the two instantly became friends.<ref>[https://www.forbes.com/feeds/ap/2009/07/06/ap6623221.html Brooke Shields talks about `asexual' Jackson] Associated Press, 07.06.09</ref> Shields said:\n\n{{quote|Thinking back to when we met and the many times that we spent together and whenever we were out together, there would be a caption of some kind, and the caption usually said something like 'an odd couple' or 'an unlikely pair,' but to us it was the most natural and easiest of friendships... Michael always knew he could count on me to support him or be his date and that we would have fun no matter where we were. We had a bond... Both of us needed to be adults very early, but when we were together, we were two little kids having fun.<ref>[http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1615431/20090707/jackson_michael.jhtml \"Brooke Shields Remembers Her Friend At Michael Jackson Memorial\"] Jul 7 2009, MTV.com</ref>}}\n\nIn her [[eulogy]], she shared anecdotes, including an occasion in which she was his date for one of [[Elizabeth Taylor]]'s weddings, and the pair sneaked into Taylor's room to get the first look at her dress, only to discover Taylor asleep in the bed. Shields gave a tearful speech, referring to the many memories she and Jackson shared and briefly joked about his famous sequin glove. She also mentioned Jackson's favorite song \"[[Smile (Charlie Chaplin song)|Smile]]\" by [[Charlie Chaplin]], which was later sung in the memorial service by [[Jermaine Jackson]].<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/music/2009/jul/07/michael-jackson-memorial-moments Michael Jackson memorial: moments to remember] Helen Pidd, ''The Guardian'', Tuesday July 7, 2009</ref>\n\n''[[New York Times]]'' columnist [[Gail Collins]] wrote that \"it was a little peculiar hearing Brooke Shields's weepy testimony about her deep friendship with Jackson given the fact that she told reporters that the last time she saw him was at Elizabeth Taylor's eighth wedding in 1991.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/07/09/opinion/09collins.html|work=The New York Times|title=Michael, a Foreign Affair|first=Gail|last=Collins|date=July 9, 2009|accessdate=April 27, 2010}}</ref> Jackson stated in his 1993 interview with [[Oprah Winfrey]] that he was dating Shields at the time.<ref>[http://www.allmichaeljackson.com/interviews/oprahinterview.html \"Michael Jackson Interview with [[Oprah Winfrey]]\" All Michael Jackson web site</ref> Shields has stated that Jackson asked her to marry him numerous times and to adopt a child together.<ref>[https://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/29126877/michael_jackson_remembered_brooke_shields_on_king_of_pops_pure_soul \"Michael Jackson Remembered: Brooke Shields on King of Pop's Pure Soul\"] Rolling Stone  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090722014547/http://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/29126877/michael_jackson_remembered_brooke_shields_on_king_of_pops_pure_soul |date=July 22, 2009 }}</ref>\n\nIn a conversation with [[Rabbi]] [[Shmuley Boteach]] in 2001, Jackson said of Shields:\n\n{{quote|That was one of the loves of my life. I think she loved me as much as I loved her, you know? We dated a lot. We, we went out a lot. Her pictures were all over my wall, my mirror, everything. And I went to the Academy Awards with Diana Ross and this girl walks up to me and says 'Hi, I'm Brooke Shields.' Then she goes, 'Are you going to the after-party?' I go, 'Yeah.' 'Good, I'll see you at the party.' I'm going, 'Oh my God, does she know she's all over my room?' So we go to the after-party. She comes up to me she goes, 'Will you dance with me?' I went, 'Yes. I will dance with you.' Man, we exchanged numbers and I was up all night, singing, spinning around my room, just so happy. It was great.<ref>[http://www.nbcnews.com/id/32987303 \"Children 'saved me,' Michael Jackson said \u2013 Taped talks between King of Pop, spiritual adviser released for first time\"], ''[[Dateline NBC]]'', September 25, 2008 (transcript)</ref>}}\n\n== Filmography ==\n=== Film ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Notes\n|-\n| 1976\n| ''[[Alice, Sweet Alice]]''\n| Karen Spages\n|\n|-\n| 1978\n| ''[[Pretty Baby (1978 film)|Pretty Baby]]''\n| Violet\n|\n|-\n| 1978\n| ''[[King of the Gypsies (film)|King of the Gypsies]]''\n| Tita\n|\n|-\n| 1979\n| ''[[Tilt (1979 film)|Tilt]]''\n| Tilt\n|\n|-\n| 1979\n| ''[[Wanda Nevada]]''\n| Wanda Nevada\n|\n|-\n| 1979\n| ''[[Just You and Me, Kid]]''\n| Kate\n|\n|-\n| 1980\n| ''[[The Blue Lagoon (1980 film)|The Blue Lagoon]]''\n| Emmeline Lestrange\n|\n|-\n| 1981\n| ''[[Endless Love (1981 film)|Endless Love]]''\n| Jade Butterfield\n|\n|-\n| 1983\n| ''[[Sahara (1983 film)|Sahara]]''\n| Dale\n|\n|-\n| 1984\n| ''[[The Muppets Take Manhattan]]''\n| Customer\n|\n|-\n| 1989\n| ''[[Speed Zone]]''\n| Stewardess\n|\n|-\n| 1989\n| ''[[Brenda Starr (1989 film)|Brenda Starr]]''\n| Brenda Starr\n|\n|-\n| 1990\n| ''[[Backstreet Dreams (film)|Backstreet Dreams]]''\n| Stevie\n|\n|-\n| 1992\n| ''[[Running Wild (1992 film)|Running Wild]]''\n| Christine Shaye\n|\n|-\n| 1993\n| ''[[Freaked]]''\n| Skye Daley\n|\n|-\n| 1994\n| ''The Postgraduate''\n| Fantasy Wife\n|\n|-\n| 1994\n| ''[[The Seventh Floor (1994 film)|The Seventh Floor]]''\n| Kate Fletcher\n|\n|-\n| 1996\n| ''[[Freeway (1996 film)|Freeway]]''\n| Mimi Wolverton\n|\n|-\n| 1998\n| ''[[The Misadventures of Margaret]]''\n| Lily\n|\n|-\n| 1999\n| ''The Weekend''\n| Nina\n|\n|-\n| 1999\n| ''[[Black and White (1999 drama film)|Black and White]]''\n| Sam Donager\n|\n|-\n| 1999\n| ''[[The Bachelor (1999 film)|The Bachelor]]''\n| Buckley Hale-Windsor\n|\n|-\n| 1999\n| ''[[The Disenchanted Forest]]''\n| Herself\n|\n|-\n| 2000\n| ''[[After Sex (2000 film)|After Sex]]''\n| Kate\n|\n|-\n| 2004\n| ''[[Our Italian Husband]]''\n| Charlene Taylor\n|\n|-\n| 2004\n| ''The Easter Egg Adventure''\n| Horrible Harriet Hare\n|Voice\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''[[Bob the Butler]]''\n| Anne Jamieson\n|\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[National Lampoon's Bag Boy]]''\n| Mrs. Hart\n|\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[Justice League: The New Frontier]]''\n| Carol Ferris\n| Voice; [[Direct-to-video|Direct-to-DVD release]]\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[The Midnight Meat Train]]''\n| Susan Hoff\n|\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[Unstable Fables#The Goldilocks and the 3 Bears Show|Unstable Fables: Goldilocks & 3 Bears Show]]''\n| Ruby Bear\n|Voice\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[Hannah Montana: The Movie]]''\n| Susan Stewart\n| Uncredited\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[Furry Vengeance]]''\n| Tammy Sanders\n|\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[The Other Guys]]''\n| Herself\n|\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[Chalet Girl]]''\n| Caroline\n|\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[The Greening of Whitney Brown]]''\n| Joan Brown\n|\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''[[The Hot Flashes]]''\n| Beth Humphrey\n|\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''A Monsterous Holiday''\n|Betsy\n| Voice\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''Under Wraps''\n| Jean\n| Voice\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''Adventure Planet''\n|\n| Voice\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Daisy Winters]]''\n| Sandy Winters\n|\n|}\n\n=== Television ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Notes\n|-\n| 1974\n| ''After the Fall''\n| Quentin's Daughter\n| Television movie\n|-\n| 1977\n| ''The Prince of Central Park''\n| Kristin\n| Television movie\n|-\n| 1982\n| ''[[The Doctors (1963 TV series)|The Doctors]]''\n| Elizabeth Harrington\n| Unknown episodes\n|-\n| 1984\n| ''[[Wet Gold]]''\n| Laura\n| Television movie\n|-\n| 1984\n| ''[[Blondes vs. Brunettes]]''\n| Herself\n| ABC television special\n|-\n| 1988\n| ''The Diamond Trap''\n| Tara Holden\n| Television movie\n|-\n| 1992\n| ''[[Quantum Leap]]''\n| Vanessa Foster\n| Episode: \"Leaping of the Shrew\"\n|-\n| 1993\n| ''[[I Can Make You Love Me]]''\n| Laura Black\n| Television movie\n|-\n| 1993\n| ''[[The Simpsons]]''\n| Herself (voice)\n| Episode: \"[[The Front (The Simpsons)|The Front]]\"\n|-\n| 1993\n| ''[[Tales from the Crypt (TV series)|Tales from the Crypt]]''\n| Norma\n| Episode: \"Came the Dawn\"\n|-\n| 1994\n| ''[[An American Love]]''\n| Greta\n| Television movie\n|-\n| 1995\n| ''Nothing Lasts Forever''\n| Dr. Beth Taft\n| Television movie\n|-\n| 1996\n| ''[[Friends]]''\n| Erika Ford\n| Episode: \"The One After the Superbowl: Part 1\"\n|-\n| 1996\u20132000\n| ''[[Suddenly Susan]]''\n| Susan Keane\n| 93 episodes, producer\n|-\n| 1998\n| ''The Almo